Comparing Gene Expression Patterns between Neuroblastoma Cell Lines

Chloe Brook

Data Introduction

  • Whole-transcriptome RNA-Seq data for 38 neuroblastoma cell lines and 3 non-neuroblastoma cell lines (RPE-1, human fetal brain tissue, and rhabdomyosarcoma) was published by Harenza et al. (2017).
  • Table containing processed FPKM data for each cell line was provided: will use this to look at expression of different genes in each cell line.

FPKM: Gene fragments per kilobase of exons per million reads.
Used as a measure of relative gene expression.

  • MYCN amplification status of each cell line was also provided in a separate text file.
  • The MYCN gene encodes the N-Myc helix-loop-helix protein.
  • Elevated MYCN gene copy number in neuroblastoma tumours is a known indicator of poor prognosis (Tonini et al. 1997)

NOTE: a corrigendum to the dataset was issued in December 2017, stating that the NB-16 cell line had been incorrectly labelled and was actually a rhabdomyosarcoma cell line (RD). Data sets have been modified to reflect this.

Aims

  • Study how gene expression varies between different cell lines used in neuroblastoma research, focusing on the differences between MYCN-amplified and non-amplified cell lines.
  • Compare mean FPKM levels of all genes in each cell line to see whether overall levels of gene expression vary between cell lines.
  • Look at the expression patterns of individual genes across cell lines.
  • Look at cell lines with similar patterns of overall gene expression, and highlight outlying cell lines.

Mean FPKM Levels of Cell Lines

The average FPKM values for all genes in each cell line were calculated and plotted in the bar chart below. Cell lines were coloured by their MYCN amplification status, to see if this had an effect on overall levels of gene expression within the cell line.

Gene Expression Heatmap

The 30 most abundant genes across all of the cell lines were selected, and the FPKM values for these genes in each cell line were mapped in the heatmap below. FPKM values were logged to base 10, to highlight differences in gene expression levels.

  • Two genes show visibly higher FPKM values against the other genes: RPPH1 and RMRP
    • Ribonuclease P RNA Component H1 (RPPH1)
    • RNA Component Of Mitochondrial RNA Processing Endoribonuclease (RMRP)
  • The gene DDX1 shows perhaps the most varied pattern of expression across the cell lines, with low FPKM values in some cell lines but very high FPKM values in others.
    • DEAD-Box Helicase 1 (DDX1)

Principal Component Analysis

Principal component analysis (PCA) is an unsupervised machine learning method used to simplify data with lots of variables into smaller dimensions called ‘principal components’.
Important features of the data are retained, and can be used to see whether variance is similar between data points (cell lines in this case).

A more thorough explanation of PCA can be found in this Nature Methods article.

PCA plot

Conclusions

The PCA plot highlights cell lines with patterns of gene expression that differ greatly from others.

  • SK-N-AS
  • KELLY
  • LAN-6
  • RD

It is notable that the cell lines furthest from centre are non-MYCN amplified. The cancerous phenotypes of these cell lines may perhaps be caused by other large aberrations in gene expression.
As RD is a rhabdomyosarcoma cell line, it makes sense that its gene expression differs from the neuroblastoma cell lines.

What makes these cell lines different from the others?

Further Work

  • Investigate genes that are differentially expressed in the outlying cell lines on the PCA plot.
  • Study pathways involved in neuroblastoma disease and drug resistance, and make PCA plots to investigate expression of these genes specifically.
